### Detailed comparison

#### Image capture (host → image)

| Aspect | clustervisor `cv-cloner new-image` | clustr `clustr image capture` / `POST /api/v1/factory/capture` |
|---|---|---|
| Capture transport | `rsync -a -h --numeric-ids --human-readable -A -H -X --filter '-x system.*' --filter '-x security.selinux' --info=progress2` from node → server `rsync_url`. | `rsync` to `internal/deploy/rsync.go`. Excludes a fixed list (`/proc/*`, `/sys/*`, `/dev/*`, `/run/*`, `/tmp/*`, `/var/tmp/*`, `/var/cache/*`, `/var/log/*`, `/boot/efi/*`, `/lost+found`, `/mnt/*`, `/media/*`, `/root/.bash_history`, `/home/*/.bash_history`, `/home/*/.ssh/authorized_keys`). |
| xattr / ACL preservation | **Yes** — `-A -H -X` (ACLs, hardlinks, xattrs), with explicit filters for `system.*` and `security.selinux`. Also separately rsyncs `.cloner` xattr/acl staging when `store-xattr-acls` is set. | Not explicitly preserved in capture path; the streamExtract in deploy uses `tar` whose flag set is determined elsewhere — needs verification (see "Gaps", below). |
| Disk layout capture | Separate operation: `cv-cloner new-disklayout` / `update-disklayout`. Stored as a versioned `cloner_disk_layout` object referencing disks, RAID, LVM, filesystems, bootloader (incl. EFI mountpoints). | The Layout package (`internal/image/layout/`) generates a *recommended* layout from hardware; not "captured" from the running node. |
| BIOS settings capture | `cv-cloner biossettings` / `biossettings-upload`. Reads via `intel-syscfg`. | None. |
| Filesystem-vs-block | Filesystem only (rsync). | Both: `ImageFormatFilesystem` (tar) and `ImageFormatBlock` (raw). |
| Validation summary before send | `show_summary_info($layout, "new-image")` interactive confirm. | None — capture starts immediately. |
| Versioning | Image options + disk layout each carry their own versions; `update-options` modifies metadata only. | Image revisions implicit via image_id; metadata mutable through `PUT /api/v1/images/{id}/tags` + `metadata`. |

#### Image storage on the server

| Aspect | clustervisor | clustr |
|---|---|---|
| On-disk format | rsync'd live tree under `<image_dir>/<image>/...` plus `.cloner/` staging dir for xattr/acl. Image options stored as YAML/JSON in DB. | Filesystem image: extracted rootfs tree at `/var/lib/clustr/images/<id>/rootfs/` with sha256 over the directory. Block image: single raw file. Image record in SQLite. |
| Compression at rest | None — rsync tree. | None — the streamed blob is recomposed from the rootfs tree on every download (`tar -cf - <rootfs>/`); compression is requested per-stream by the client (nothing is gzipped on disk). |
| Deduplication | Implicit via rsync delta on update. | None. |
| Resumable build | Server-side state machine for resumable downloads (`018_image_build_resumable.sql`). Phases tracked. `Factory.ResumeFromPhase()`. | Same on clustr side; this is parity. |
| Image kinds | `cloner_image` (filesystem to deploy on disk), `diskless_image` (NFS-rooted), stateless image (initramfs+squashfs in RAM). | Single `BaseImage` (with `Format=filesystem|block`); no diskless / stateless model. |
| Build manifest signing | None of the cloner trees are signed end-to-end (the SLURM bundles are, separately). | clustr signs the build manifest of every image and exposes it at `/api/v1/images/{id}/build-manifest`. |

#### Image transport to the deploying node

| Aspect | clustervisor | clustr |
|---|---|---|
| Default transport | `rsync -a -h --numeric-ids` from server to node, with `--bwlimit` configurable per image. | HTTP GET `/api/v1/images/{id}/blob` streamed → tar. Throughput watchdog (cancel if <1 KB/s for 120 s). pigz / zstd auto-detect for compression. |
| Multicast | **Yes** — UDPCast. Server tracks readiness in `_cloner_multicast` collection per IP, expires after 90 s, base port 9000 (configurable). Each batch picks next port. Receiver runs `udp-receiver --pipe 'tar --extract --xattrs-include='security.*' --xattrs-include='user.*' --acls'`. Sender side runs `udp-sender` for the tarball. | **No.** Every node pulls its own copy over HTTP. |
| Offline / USB | **Yes** — `cv-cloner make-installer` builds a USB image carrying the cloner initrd + a chosen image. Installer mounts USB and does `rsync` from `/cloner/usb/<image>` instead of network. | **No.** Initramfs is network-only. |
| Bandwidth limit | rsync `--bwlimit` per image option. | None. |
| Resumable (per-stream) | rsync handles partial transfers natively. | clustr re-issues the HTTP GET on stream failure (the rsync.go retry loop) but always re-runs from byte 0 — no Range: support on client side. |
| Integrity | Per-rsync checksum + post-install verify. | sha256 over the streamed tar (header `X-Clustr-Blob-SHA256`); verified post-extract. |
| Authentication | Munge sign+verify on every API call. SSH-equivalent trust on rsync (uses `rsync://` daemon mode on the server with auth). | Bearer token (node-scoped, single-use within a deploy run). |
| Maximum practical concurrency | High via multicast (single tar stream addressed to N receivers). | Limited by server NIC bandwidth ÷ image size; no practical reimage-fleet flow. |

#### Initramfs build pipeline

| Aspect | clustervisor (Buildroot) | clustr (`scripts/build-initramfs.sh`) |
|---|---|---|
| Builder | Buildroot 2019.02-00050. `external.{desc,mk}` overlay tree at `/usr/libexec/clustervisor/cloner_initrd/initrd/buildroot-act-tree/`. Make-driven, reproducible. | 1,300-line bash. Pulls busybox-musl from `https://busybox.net/downloads/binaries/1.35.0-x86_64-linux-musl/busybox` (sha256-pinned). Pulls kernel modules over `sshpass` from `192.168.1.151` (a hardcoded dev box) unless `CLUSTR_CI_MODE=1`. |
| Architectures | x86_64 nocona only (per `BR2_GCC_TARGET_ARCH="nocona"`). | linux/amd64 only; no aarch64 path despite RPM split. |
| Per-distro variants | Three initrd source tarballs: `initrd-src-cloner.tar.bz2`, `initrd-src-el7-cloner.tar.bz2`, `initrd-src-el8-cloner.tar.bz2` (no el9 in this build — points to a separate generation path). | Single initramfs; the kernel modules pulled at build time tie it to a specific kernel version. |
| Reproducibility | Reproducible across rebuilds (Buildroot pins package SHA + version per `external.desc`). | Mostly: busybox sha256-pinned; kernel modules vary per server source; bash logic is procedural and order-dependent. |
| Networking modules | Detected at runtime (`load_all_kmod` skipping class "network", then auto-detect via PCI). | Hardcoded list: `failover`, `net_failover`, `virtio_net`, `virtio_scsi`, `sd_mod`, `virtio_blk`, `crc32c-intel`, `libcrc32c`, `xfs`, `ext4`, `fat`, `vfat`, `raid0/1/10/456`. **No Mellanox (mlx4/5), no Intel ixgbe/i40e, no broadcom, no megaraid_sas, no mpt3sas.** |
| Storage modules | Auto + manual lists (kmod, kmod-blacklist, kmod-post per image config). | Same hardcoded list as above; raid0/1/10/456 included; **no btrfs, no zfs, no dm_crypt, no nvme** (despite the deploy code being NVMe-aware). |
| Bundled tools | busybox + dropbear + mdadm + nvme + lvm2 + e2fsprogs + xfsprogs + btrfs-progs + dosfstools + smartmontools + hdparm + dmidecode + ipmitool (lanplus + USB) + udpcast (sender + receiver) + rsync + tar + xz + openssl + util-linux blkid/uuid + perl + munge. **116 packages total.** | busybox + dropbear + mdadm + mkfs.{xfs,ext4,vfat} + partprobe (parted) + rsync + cpio (build host only) + clustr static binary. **About 8 binaries plus busybox applets.** |
| Authentication artefact | `/etc/munge/munge.key` baked into initrd; `/etc/dropbear/` SSH host keys baked in. | None baked in. SSH host key generated at boot. Auth via per-boot `clustr.token=` from kernel cmdline. |
| Init system | SysV with `S10mdev` → `S50dropbear` → `S55munged` → `cloner_start.sh` → `installer` (Perl) → exec `/bin/ash`. | Single bash `init.sh` template with placeholders substituted at build time. Mounts proc/sys/dev/devpts, mdev, parses cmdline, insmod hardcoded list, polls block devices for 45 s, udhcpc on each iface, starts httpd serving init.log on port 9999, exec `clustr deploy --auto`. |
| Diagnostics | Dropbear SSH always available; `/etc/munge/munge.key` allows trusted ops. | Per-boot dropbear password (8-char hex) embedded in cmdline; init log served on port 9999 over HTTP for the server to fetch. |

#### Disk preparation + bootloader

| Aspect | clustervisor (`ClonerInstall.pm`) | clustr (`internal/deploy/`) |
|---|---|---|
| Partitioning tool | parted + mdadm + lvm. Distinct paths for IMSM (Intel Matrix Storage Manager onboard RAID). | sgdisk (`backup_partition_table`/`restore_partition_table`/`probe`). mdadm for software RAID. |
| Filesystems supported in installer | xfs, ext{2,3,4}, fat, swap, btrfs (Buildroot includes btrfs-progs). | xfs, ext4, vfat (matching the mkfs.* binaries shipped in initramfs). ZFS supported in deploy code (`zfs.go`) but no `zpool` binary in initramfs. |
| Hardware RAID | IMSM (Intel RST/IMSM) supported via `disk_raid_imsm()`. Falls back to `disk_raid_standard()`. | None (pure mdadm software RAID). No IMSM passthrough; no megaraid CLI; no PERC. |
| Disk layout source | Per-image versioned `cloner_disk_layout` object that has been previously captured + uploaded. | `Layout.Recommend` derives layout from hardware on each deploy; `Layout.Validate` + `Layout.Autocorrect` catch obvious mistakes. |
| /etc/fstab generation | `create_fstab()` from blkid UUIDs. | `internal/deploy/finalize.go` `writeFstab` (similar). |
| /etc/mdadm.conf generation | `create_mdadm_conf()` from mdadm --detail --scan. | `internal/deploy/raid.go` writes mdadm conf. |
| Distro-specific system files | Separate generators for el7 (`_create_system_files_el7`), el8 (`_create_system_files_el8`), el9 (`_create_system_files_el`), ubuntu (`_create_system_files_ubuntu`), with ifcfg-style for el7/8, NetworkManager for el9, netplan for ubuntu. | `finalize.go` + `network.go` generate NetworkManager keyfiles for el9. el7/el8 ifcfg-style not present. Ubuntu / Debian not supported in deploy at all. |
| Bootloader install | `install_bootloader_grub()` (BIOS) and `install_bootloader_efi()` (UEFI). Per-distro grub.cfg generators (`_generate_grub2_config_el`, `_generate_grub2_config_el9`, `_generate_grub2_config_ubuntu`). | `internal/deploy/efiboot.go` for UEFI (`grub2-install --removable` writes `\EFI\BOOT\BOOTX64.EFI`; no NVRAM entry created). BIOS path uses grub2-install with `--target=i386-pc`. UEFI BootOrder rotation with `efibootmgr -o` post-install. `BootloaderError` if `grub2-install` fails on all targets. |
| EFI repair | `cv-cloner fix-efiboot` — uses `EFIBootmgr.pm` to inspect/recreate boot entries. | `clustr fix-efi-boot` CLI subcommand (`newFixEFIBootCmd`). Parity. |
| BIOS settings push | `check_set_biossettings` → `_check_set_intel_syscfg` → `_set_intel_bios_setting` / `_check_intel_bios_setting`. Compares current vs desired Intel server BIOS settings via `intel-syscfg`. | None. |
| IPMI configuration | `configure_ipmi` — writes channel LAN settings, VLAN, DHCP/static, gateway, user/password per channel. | clustr CLI has `clustr ipmi configure` for operator-side setup; the in-installer path doesn't auto-configure BMC LAN. |

#### Post-install instruction processing

| Aspect | clustervisor | clustr |
|---|---|---|
| Per-image install instructions | Each image carries an `install_instructions` array. Three opcodes: **modify** (patch a file in-place), **overwrite** (replace a file with a templated one), **script** (run a shell snippet inside the chroot). Ordered, sequential. Failure aborts. | None. The deploy `finalize` phase has fixed steps (hostname, network, fstab, mdadm conf, ssh host keys, grub2-install, install clustr-clientd, sysaccounts inject, network/keyfile gen). |
| `cv-reconfigure` inside chroot | Yes — runs every config plugin (chronyd, fstab, hosts, ldapauth, rsyslog, selinux, slurmclient, ssh, sudoers, timezone, tuned, yumrepo, etc.) against the freshly installed root. | clientd applies the per-node config *after* boot, on the live system. No in-chroot reconfigure pass. Means the very first boot may have an old `/etc/hosts` until clientd connects. |
| clientd injection | `install_cvclient_reconfigure` writes the cv-clientd RPM into the chroot and enables it via systemd. | `internal/deploy/clientd_inject.go` writes the clustr-clientd binary into the chroot, drops `/etc/clustr/clustrd-url` and `/etc/clustr/node-token`, and enables `clustr-clientd.service` via systemd-systemctl preset. |

#### Diskless / stateless boot path

| Aspect | clustervisor | clustr |
|---|---|---|
| Diskless image | `cv-diskless new/edit/kernel/prep/state/exec/cp` workflow. Image is NFS-exported root fs. Node mounts root via NFS at boot. | None. |
| Stateless image | `iPXEserver._ipxe_stateless_entry` — per-image stateless entries in iPXE menu. Server lists `get_stateless_servers()`. Node boots a kernel + initramfs that fetches a squashfs into RAM. | None (P2 in original section). |
| Combination with DHCP/TFTP | clustervisor expects external dhcpd / DNS; uses its own iPXE TFTP. | clustr's embedded DHCP+TFTP+iPXE chain handles all of this. |

#### iPXE menu generation

| Aspect | clustervisor (`ipxe_server.py`) | clustr (`internal/pxe/boot.go`) |
|---|---|---|
| Menu source | Python class builds menu from server config: `ipxe_menu(default, default_timeout)`, `_ipxe_global_entries`, `_ipxe_netboot_entry`, `_ipxe_stateless_entry`. Each node can have a per-MAC menu. | Go template baked into the binary. Per-node menu uses node state machine routing (`generateDiskBootScript` + `GenerateBootScript` + `GenerateWaitRetryScript`). |
| Boot menu items | Custom per-node + per-image entries. Stateless entries tied to specific image-node pairs. Netboot entries (custom OS installers, memtest, etc.). | Three: `disk` (sanboot 0x80), `reimage` (chain back with `force_reimage=1`), `rescue` ("not yet configured"). |
| Branding | Generic Cockpit/clustervisor branding. | Branded `c l o n r   B o o t   M a n a g e r` ASCII header with version + node + MAC info. |
| Per-firmware behavior | Common iPXE syntax across BIOS + UEFI. | Two separate templates (`diskBootBIOSTemplate` and a UEFI variant). BIOS uses `sanboot --no-describe --drive 0x80` (avoids SeaBIOS PXE-loop bug); UEFI chains `grub.efi` from the server. |
| Token / auth | Munge-based — token comes via munge-signed JSON. | Per-boot node-scoped API key minted at PXE-serve time, embedded as `clustr.token=` and `clustr.ssh.pass=` in the kernel cmdline. SSH password is logged at INFO so the operator can find it via journalctl. |

### Gap analysis (cloning + initramfs)

The 14 most consequential gaps, prioritised by operational impact.

#### CG1 — UDPCast multicast for fleet reimaging — 🔴 Major

**Problem**: clustr's blob is HTTP from server → node, one stream per node.
A 50-node reimage of a 10 GB image saturates a 1 Gbps NIC at the server for
the entire transfer (~14 minutes per node × 50 nodes ÷ NIC bandwidth, in
practice the server is the bottleneck). clustervisor solves this with
UDPCast: one `udp-sender` on the server fans out to N `udp-receiver`
processes on the nodes; total time ≈ single-node transfer time + a small
constant overhead.

**Recommendation**:

- Add `udpcast` (sender + receiver) to the initramfs (Buildroot equivalent —
  see CG6).
- Add a server-side multicast scheduler (`internal/multicast/`):
  - DB table `multicast_sessions(image_id, port, started_at, expires_at, leader_node_id)`.
  - When a deploy starts and N other nodes are already in `multicast_pending`
    state for the same image, pause the new arrivals up to a configurable
    window (default 60 s) so they batch. Then start one `udp-sender` for
    the whole batch.
  - Each receiver pipes through tar with `--xattrs-include='security.*' --acls`
    (clustervisor's pattern).
- Add a clustr CLI flag `clustr deploy --multicast=auto|off|require` to
  let operators force one mode or the other.
- New iPXE menu item: "Reimage (wait for fleet)" vs "Reimage (now)".

**Time estimate**: 4–5 weeks (initramfs work + scheduler + receiver wiring +
tests on the lab).

#### CG2 — Hardware-realistic kernel modules in initramfs — 🔴 Major

**Problem**: `scripts/initramfs-init.sh` insmod's a hardcoded virtio-only
list. A real HPC node will have any of: `mlx4_core` / `mlx5_core` / `mlx5_ib`
(Mellanox CX-3/4/5/6/7 IB+ETH), `i40e` / `ice` / `ixgbe` (Intel 10/25/40/100
GbE), `bnxt_en` (Broadcom), `megaraid_sas` (LSI/Avago SAS HBAs), `mpt3sas`
(Avago), `nvme` (already missing despite NVMe deploy support), `bnx2x`,
`tg3` — none of which clustr currently loads. On real hardware the deploy
agent will fail at "no usable NIC found".

**Recommendation**:

- Switch to **auto-load** style: instead of an explicit `insmod` list,
  use `find /lib/modules/$KVER/kernel -name "*.ko*"` + a curated allowlist,
  or `modprobe -a` with module aliases pulled from `lspci -k`.
- Or, if staying with explicit lists, expand to cover at minimum:
  `failover`, `net_failover`, `virtio_*`,
  `mlx5_core`, `mlx5_ib`, `mlx4_core`, `mlx4_en`,
  `i40e`, `ice`, `ixgbe`, `igb`, `e1000e`,
  `bnxt_en`, `bnx2x`, `tg3`,
  `nvme`, `nvme_core`,
  `megaraid_sas`, `mpt3sas`, `aacraid`,
  `dm_mod`, `dm_log`, `dm_region_hash`,
  `xfs`, `ext4`, `fat`, `vfat`, `btrfs`,
  `raid0`, `raid1`, `raid10`, `raid456`,
  `crc32c-intel`, `libcrc32c`, `crc32c_generic`.
- Build the kernel-module manifest at initramfs-build time by enumerating
  `/lib/modules/$KVER/kernel/{net,drivers/net,drivers/scsi,drivers/block,drivers/md,drivers/nvme,fs}/`
  and copying every `.ko*` whose name matches the allowlist. Print a
  manifest of what was included into a build artifact for debugging.

**Time estimate**: 1–2 weeks.

#### CG3 — xattr / ACL preservation in deploy — 🟠 Medium-major

**Problem**: clustervisor's installer pipes the multicast/rsync stream
through `tar --xattrs-include='security.*' --xattrs-include='user.*' --acls`
so SELinux contexts and POSIX ACLs survive the install. clustr's
`streamExtract` runs `tar` (the in-initramfs busybox `tar`) without
explicitly specifying `--xattrs-include` / `--acls`. Busybox `tar`
historically does not preserve xattrs or ACLs. On SELinux-enforcing
deployments the relabel post-install can mask this, but ACLs are silently
dropped.

**Recommendation**:

- Audit the actual `tar` invocation in `internal/deploy/rsync.go`'s
  `streamExtract`. If it uses busybox `tar`, swap for GNU `tar` (already
  in the Buildroot equivalent for clustervisor; ship via the bundled
  binaries list in `scripts/build-initramfs.sh`).
- Add `--xattrs --xattrs-include='*' --acls` flags.
- Add an integration test under `internal/deploy/` that captures an image
  with selinux contexts + POSIX ACLs and asserts they survive deploy →
  capture round-trips.

**Time estimate**: 1 week.

#### CG4 — USB / offline cloner installer — 🟠 Medium-major

**Problem**: `cv-cloner make-installer` builds a USB image that contains
the cloner initrd plus a chosen image. The node boots from USB, identifies
itself, and rsyncs from `/cloner/usb/<image>` instead of network. This is
how clustervisor handles air-gapped, slow-WAN, or PXE-blocked sites. clustr
is fully network-dependent.

**Recommendation**:

- New CLI: `clustr-serverd installer build --image <id> --output <iso|img>`
  that produces a hybrid ISO/USB image:
  - The clustr initramfs + a kernel
  - The image blob (tarball) embedded
  - A small init shim that detects "USB/ISO" boot vs "PXE" and points the
    deploy agent at a local `file://` URL.
- Document the operator workflow: `dd if=clustr-installer.iso of=/dev/sdX`
  → boot the target → it auto-deploys.
- Optionally support hybrid ISOs that boot both BIOS (isolinux) and UEFI
  (grub.efi) so the same media works on any hardware.

**Time estimate**: 3 weeks.

#### CG5 — BIOS settings push (intel-syscfg + Dell racadm + Supermicro SUM) — 🟠 Medium-major

**Problem**: clustervisor's `check_set_biossettings` reads/writes Intel
server BIOS settings via `intel-syscfg` (Buildroot package
`intel-syscfg/syscfg-V14_1_Build24.tar.gz`). HPC operators frequently
need to enforce things like SMT off, HT on, P-states, NUMA snoop mode,
power profiles, IPMI watchdog timer settings — at scale, on every
reimage. clustr has none of this.

**Recommendation**:

- New `internal/bios/` package with vendor providers:
  - `internal/bios/intel/` — wrap `intel-syscfg`.
  - `internal/bios/dell/` — wrap `racadm` (DRAC).
  - `internal/bios/supermicro/` — wrap `sum` (SUM).
- New table `bios_profiles(id, name, vendor, settings_json)` and
  `node_bios_profile(node_id, profile_id, last_applied_at)`.
- Add a deploy phase that runs after partition/format and before image
  extract: read desired profile, diff against current (via the same vendor
  CLI), apply if drift, log to audit.
- Bundle the vendor binaries in the initramfs (small footprint each).

**Time estimate**: 4–5 weeks (vendor binaries vary; Intel is the easiest
starting point, Dell next).

#### CG6 — Switch initramfs build to a reproducible builder — 🟠 Medium

**Problem**: `scripts/build-initramfs.sh` is 1,300 lines of bash with
external assumptions: a specific dev-box at 192.168.1.151 over SSH, a pinned
busybox URL on busybox.net, and PATH-dependent system tools. It works on
the cloner host and in CI; it's brittle outside those environments. Build
output isn't reproducible byte-for-byte.

**Recommendations** (pick one):

- **Option A** (lighter): keep bash, but replace the SSH-pull with a
  Make-driven local kernel-module extraction step and ship a Dockerfile
  that contains the build environment so anyone can `docker run
  ghcr.io/sqoia-dev/clustr-initramfs-builder:latest` to get bit-identical
  output.
- **Option B** (heavier, longer-term): adopt **dracut** modules for the
  per-distro variant or move to **Buildroot** like clustervisor. Buildroot
  is reproducible, supports cross-compile to aarch64 (closes the arm64 gap),
  and has out-of-the-box packages for everything in CG2 + CG4 (busybox,
  dropbear, mdadm, lvm2, e2fsprogs, xfsprogs, btrfs-progs, dosfstools,
  smartmontools, hdparm, dmidecode, ipmitool, udpcast, rsync, gnu tar, xz,
  openssl, util-linux, intel-syscfg).

**Time estimate**: 1 week (Option A) or 4 weeks (Option B).

#### CG7 — Decouple disk layout from image — 🟠 Medium

**Problem**: clustervisor's `cloner_disk_layout` is a separate first-class
object — captured from a representative node, versioned, edited
independently, and referenced by name from any image. clustr's layout is
either auto-recommended at deploy time or attached to the image record;
operators who have a specific known-good partition scheme for a node class
can't say "use layout 'compute-h100-v3' on every node in this group."

**Recommendation**:

- New table `disk_layouts(id, name, source_node_id, captured_at, layout_json)`.
- New endpoints `POST /api/v1/disk-layouts/capture/{node_id}`,
  `GET /api/v1/disk-layouts`, `PUT /api/v1/disk-layouts/{id}`.
- New foreign key `node_groups.disk_layout_id` (and per-node override).
- Deploy agent prefers explicit layout > group default > recommendation.
- UI: "Disk Layouts" tab on the **Images** route (or its own tab).

**Time estimate**: 2 weeks.

#### CG8 — Image install instructions DSL — 🟡 Medium

**Problem**: clustervisor's per-image `install_instructions` array
(opcodes: modify, overwrite, script) gives operators a small declarative
hook to customise an image without re-baking it. Need to set a different
`/etc/motd` on the storage role? Add an instruction. Need to drop a
custom kickstart-time script into `/usr/local/bin/`? Add an instruction.
clustr today requires a full image rebuild (or relying on clientd's
post-boot config apply).

**Recommendation**:

- Extend `BaseImage` with `install_instructions []InstallInstruction`.
- `InstallInstruction = { opcode: "modify"|"overwrite"|"script",
  target: string, payload: string }`.
- Deploy agent runs them in order inside the chroot after extract,
  before bootloader install.
- UI: "Install Instructions" tab on the image edit drawer.

**Time estimate**: 1.5 weeks.

#### CG9 — IMSM / hardware RAID passthrough in installer — 🟡 Medium

**Problem**: Intel Matrix Storage Manager (IMSM) onboard RAID is common
on Xeon servers; clustervisor handles it via `disk_raid_imsm()` in
`ClonerInstall.pm`. clustr installer cannot deploy to IMSM-managed disks
today.

**Recommendation**:

- Add `mdadm --imsm-platform-test` detection in `internal/deploy/raid.go`.
- Branch on detection: assemble IMSM container, then create the volume,
  then format inside.
- Add tests using qemu IMSM-emulated topology.

**Time estimate**: 1.5 weeks.

#### CG10 — Per-stream Range: support for blob retries — 🟡 Medium

**Problem**: `internal/deploy/rsync.go`'s blob retry loop re-issues the
HTTP GET from byte 0 on stream failure. For a 20 GB image over a flaky
WAN link this is fatal — every glitch sends you back to the start.

**Recommendation**:

- Track bytes-received per attempt. On retry, send `Range: bytes=N-` and
  resume the tar stream. Server already serves blobs as a regular file,
  which Go's `net/http.ServeContent` honors Range requests for; verify
  end-to-end.
- Cap total retry duration at `CLUSTR_DEPLOY_TIMEOUT`.

**Time estimate**: 0.5 week.

#### CG11 — Distro coverage in installer (Ubuntu / Debian / SLES) — 🟡 Medium

**Problem**: clustr's distro support in `internal/deploy/finalize.go` +
`network.go` is el9-only. clustervisor handles el7, el8, el9, ubuntu with
distinct system-files generators.

**Recommendation**:

- Refactor `finalize.go` around a `DistroDriver` interface:
  `WriteSystemFiles(chroot, hostname, network) error`,
  `InstallBootloader(chroot, layout) error`.
- Implement drivers: `el8`, `el9`, `el10`, `ubuntu24` (matches what HPC
  sites with Ubuntu compute pools want). SLES is niche; defer.
- Plumb through image factory so it knows which DistroDriver applies.

**Time estimate**: 3 weeks.

#### CG12 — In-chroot reconfigure pass before first boot — 🟡 Medium

**Problem**: clustervisor runs `cv-reconfigure` inside the chroot
post-extract, so every config plugin (chronyd, hosts, ldapauth, rsyslog,
slurmclient, sudoers, timezone, tuned, yumrepo, etc.) lands before the
node ever boots its installed OS. clustr defers everything to clientd
post-boot. The result is that the very first boot of a freshly imaged
node has stale `/etc/hosts`, no chronyd peer config, no LDAP joined, no
slurmd running — a 30-second-to-3-minute window where the node looks
"online but useless."

**Recommendation**:

- Add a `clustr deploy --in-chroot` mode that runs the same logic as
  clientd's `configapply` against `/mnt/target` before unmount.
- The clientd code already lives at `internal/clientd/configapply.go`;
  factor out the file-writing logic so it can target an arbitrary root.

**Time estimate**: 1.5 weeks.

#### CG13 — Per-image stateless / netboot menu entries — 🟡 Medium

**Problem**: `iPXEserver` exposes per-image stateless entries
(`_ipxe_stateless_entry`) and named netboot entries (`_ipxe_netboot_entry`)
in the boot menu, so operators can boot Memtest, a custom rescue OS, an
Ubuntu installer ISO, etc., from the same iPXE menu. clustr's menu is
fixed at 3 items (disk / reimage / rescue-not-configured).

**Recommendation**:

- Add a `boot_entries` table: `id, name, kind: stateless|netboot|memtest|
  custom, kernel_url, initrd_url, cmdline, enabled`.
- Render extra menu items into the iPXE menu at PXE-serve time.
- UI: "Boot Menu" tab on the **Settings** route. Stock entries: Memtest,
  Ubuntu Live, Rescue (busybox+dropbear with credentials from the
  operator).

**Time estimate**: 2 weeks (the rescue boot needs CG2 first to actually
work on real HW).

#### CG14 — Bandwidth-limit + concurrency caps on transport — 🟢 Minor

**Problem**: rsync's `--bwlimit` lets ops cap server outbound bandwidth
during business hours. clustr has neither bandwidth caps nor a global
concurrency cap on `/api/v1/images/{id}/blob`.

**Recommendation**:

- Add `CLUSTR_BLOB_MAX_BPS` env var (per-stream cap) and
  `CLUSTR_BLOB_MAX_CONCURRENCY` (global cap). Implement via a token-bucket
  middleware in `internal/server/handlers/images.go`.

**Time estimate**: 0.5 week.

