These slot into the existing 13-iteration roadmap as follows:

| Iteration | Original focus | New imaging/UI deliverables to fold in |
|---|---|---|
| 7–8 | P1 stats agent + alerts | UP1 (per-node sensor/SEL/console panels) lands alongside stats agent. |
| 9 | P1 alerting | UP5 (Alerts UI) lands with the alerting engine. |
| 10 | P3 SNMP OOB | (no overlap) |
| 11 | P2 stateless images | CG13 (stateless menu entries) lands here. UP2 (stateless image management) UI lands here. |
| 12 | P4 two-stage commit | UP9 (changes drawer) lands here. |
| 13 | P6 + P7 | (no overlap) |

Then add a new mini-track **"CG: cloning hardening"** as iterations 14–18
once the alerting / portal work is settled:

| Iteration | Focus |
|---|---|
| 14 | CG2 (kernel modules) + CG3 (xattr/ACL) + CG10 (Range:) + CG14 (bwlimit). Small, high-leverage fixes. Closes the "real-hardware" gap. |
| 15 | CG1 (UDPCast multicast). Single biggest feature for fleet reimaging. |
| 16 | CG7 (decoupled disk layouts) + CG8 (install instructions) + CG12 (in-chroot reconfigure). Image-system maturity. |
| 17 | CG4 (USB installer) + CG6 (reproducible initramfs builder, Option A). |
| 18 | CG11 (Ubuntu distro driver) + CG9 (IMSM RAID). Hardware/distro coverage. |
| 19 | CG5 (BIOS settings push). Largest piece of work. |
| 20 | UP3/UP4/UP6/UP7/UP8/UP10/UP11. UI catch-up sprint. |

After iteration 20 the operator-facing parity gap is essentially closed:
operators can reimage 100 nodes simultaneously over multicast, push BIOS
settings as part of the deploy, edit per-image install instructions,
manage rack diagrams, see live sensors and alerts in the browser, and
build offline installer media.

### Things clustr's imaging already does *better* than clustervisor

So the team doesn't regress these:

1. **Single Go binary in the initramfs** instead of a Perl runtime + 8,200
   lines of Perl modules. Easier to debug, easier to test (`go test
   ./internal/deploy/...` actually runs). One static binary handles
   discovery, deploy, finalize, and IPMI ops.
2. **HTTP transport with sha256 verification + zstd support**. clustervisor's
   rsync is solid but doesn't sit cleanly behind a CDN or auth proxy;
   clustr's HTTP-with-bearer flow does. zstd is materially faster than
   gzip for the multi-GB tarballs HPC images tend to be.
3. **Throughput watchdog** (`newThroughputWatchdog` cancels the deploy if
   the stream stalls below 1 KB/s for 120 s) — a feature clustervisor
   doesn't have. Failure modes are bounded.
4. **Per-boot node-scoped tokens** with audit. clustervisor's munge is
   fine but not auditable per-deploy.
5. **Per-firmware iPXE branching** with the `sanboot 0x80` workaround for
   SeaBIOS / Proxmox. clustervisor's "common iPXE" is more elegant on
   real HW but breaks on virtualised lab setups.
6. **Auto-register on unknown MAC** in `BootHandler.ServeIPXEScript`:
   PXE-boot any new machine and it shows up in the inventory immediately
   with a deterministic hostname. clustervisor requires explicit pre-registration
   (or the operator runs `cv-cloner identify` from the booted system).
7. **Modern build tooling**: nfpm + dnf-repo-on-Caddy + gosec + gold
   linker; nothing in the cloner side of clustervisor uses anything later
   than 2019 (Buildroot 2019.02, Python 3.6 venv).
8. **Storage recommender** (`internal/image/layout/recommend.go`): given
   raw hardware, suggest a sensible layout including ZFS with SLOG/L2ARC
   role assignment for NVMe drives. clustervisor leaves all of this to
   the operator and a captured `cloner_disk_layout`.
9. **Deploy progress streaming** to the server with structured phases
   (`StartPhase("formatting", n)` etc.) that the UI can show live. The
   clustervisor flow logs to journald only.
10. **Backup/restore of partition table on rollback** (`backupPartitionTable`
    via `sgdisk --backup`) — non-destructive deploy with rollback. clustervisor's
    installer commits as it goes.
